title: First trip of Seattle Coal Company railroad, December 1871
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Seattle Transportation. First train coming in from Lake Union on Seattle's first railroad. Dec. 28, 1871. South end of Lake Union. Tracks followed what is now Westlake Ave." Transcribed from back of photograph: “Seattle's FIRST railroad, operated by the Seattle Coal Co., hauled coal from the south end of Lake Union to coal bunkers at the foot of Pike street; closed down when the first train service was established to Renton in 1877.
intersection: Valley St. and Westlake Ave. N.

title: Sixth St. School, ca. 1890
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Seattle Schools. Sixth Street School. Sixth Ave. and Madison. Built 1877; closed 1883; sold and moved to 8th and Columbia, 1884. Exterior. Frame. Three-quarter view. Ca. 1890. Photo by Peiser, Theodore E." Transcribed from back of photograph: "SIXTH STREET SCHOOL - erected on Central School block in 1877, preceding brick building now on site.  School is shown after it was removed to the northwest corner of 8th and Columbia, as the upper half of a two-story combination store and “flats” building.”

description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Houses. McGilvra, John J. Exterior. Laurel Shade Road. Built 1864; destroyed by fire 1933. 1870." Laurel Shade Road can be seen in the 1905 and 1912 Baist Atlases. It runs along the present-day path of 43rd Ave. E.

title: Potlatch Festival Tyee reception, July 17, 1912
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Golden Potlatch. July 15-20. Reception of the Tyee. View 2." From the Potlatch Program printed in the Seattle Times on July 16, 1912: "1:00 pm - Opening spectacle of the Golden Potlatch, 1912. The arrival of the Hyas Golden Potlatch Tyee from the Land of the North. The Hyas Tyee, attended by his tribal chiefs, his Shamans and other dignitaries of this barbaric court, arrives in Elliott Bay on the Goldship Portland. Accompanying him are many "sourdoughs," pioneers of hte North, who bring with them the first golden nuggets found in the Great Yukon. They have their "pokes," their picturesque dog sleds and other equipment of the Northern trails and they come attired in the queer dress of the North, in parks, muk-luka and all the rest. This weird crew will leave the goldship in the stream and make its landing on the waterfront, where the Hyas Tyee and his people will be greeted by the Tilikums of Elttaes who will escort them to the Grandstand on Fourth Avenue between Lenora and Blanchard Streets, where the opening ceremonies will be performed." Location of photograph presumed to be at Grandstand based on newspaper program.

title: Lake Union looking northwest, ca. 1885
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Lake Union. Looking northwest over Lake Union town. Ca. 1885. Photo by Peiser, Theodore E.. Lumber mill at right center built in 1882. The 1905 Baist Atlas shows the Western Mill on the lakefront at the intersection of Terry Ave. N. and Valley St.
intersection: Terry Ave. N. and Valley St.
